Overall Goal

The purpose of this project is to write functions that will manipulate and process data sets that come in a certain form. Also we create a generic function to automatically plot the returned data.

Data Processing

We begin by reading in one section of the data given and load tidyverse. Dplyr is part of the tidyverse.

library(tidyverse)
sheet1 <- read_csv("https://www4.stat.ncsu.edu/~online/datasets/EDU01a.csv")

We continue with the following six steps.

Step 3

Continuing the chain from Step 2, we Parse the string to pull out the year and convert the year into a numeric. This gives the two digit date as a column which we name “year2digit”. In order to do this we use the substr() and as.numeric() to convert to a numeric value

  mutate(year2digit = as.numeric(substr(as.character(ends_with_D),8,9)))

Continuing the chain from abover, since we want the 4 digit date we create a new column called “year” using mutate() and we take all the two digits from “year2digit” that are greater than or equal to 70 and add 1900 otherwise we add 2000, so for example 82 becomes 1982 and 02 becomes 2002.

We use 70 because 71 was the lowest two digit year for all the data we wish to use in this project.

sheet1renamed%>%
  
  select(area_name, STCOU, ends_with("D"))%>%
  
  pivot_longer(cols = 3:12, names_to = "ends_with_D", values_to = "enrollment_value")%>%

  mutate(year2digit = as.numeric(substr(as.character(ends_with_D),8,9)))%>%

  mutate(year=if_else(year2digit>=70,year2digit+1900,year2digit+2000))

Step 4

We use our object “to_split” and create two data sets “non_county_data” and “county_data”. We note that the county name contains “DD” where “DD” represents the state.

Using this information together with grepl() we successfully create the two data sets.

Alternatively we could use the grep with an if/else but after doing some reading on the internet I found that grepl() already returns TRUE/FALSE so there is no need for the if/else statement.

We get the county data using grepl(pattern = ", \\w\\w", area_name) and the non-county by using !grepl(pattern = ", \\w\\w", area_name). The “, \w\w” accounts for the comma and the two letters “DD” that represent county name.

  non_county_data <- filter(to_split, !grepl(pattern = ", \\w\\w", area_name))

In this section we want to repeat the above process for the 2nd component of the data set. Instead of copying and pasting the above code and modifying, we want to write functions that do the above six Steps and one function that we can call to do all six steps.

Read in code

Firstly, we read in the code in a similar manner as we did before.

sheet1 <- read_csv("https://www4.stat.ncsu.edu/~online/datasets/EDU01b.csv")

Function for Steps 1 and 2

We now create a function for steps 1 and 2. We use csv for the input and var_name = “enrollment_value” for the optional default argument value. We use the method similar to Step 1 and Step 2 as detailed in the “Data Processing” section to rename, select and pivot.

function_for_step_1_2 <- function(csv, var_name ="enrollment_value"){
  rename <- rename(csv, area_name = Area_name) #this changes Area_name to area_name
  
  select <- select(rename, area_name, STCOU, ends_with("D")) #this selects the required columns
  
  pivot <- pivot_longer(select, cols = 3:12, names_to = "ends_with_D", values_to =
                 "enrollment_value") #this converts to long format
  

  return(pivot)
}

Function taking output of Step 2 to do step 3

Next we create a function that takes in the output of step 2 outputs the desired tibble with a four digit numeric column and a new column “survey_type”.

To achieve this, in a similar manner to step 3 we create a new column called “year2digit” and convert it to a numeric value using as.numeric.

Using the “year2digit” column we create the required four digit column and delete the unwanted “year2digit” column.

Finally, we add a new column “survey_type” using the mutate() function

function_for_step_3 <- function(step2_output){
   yr_2digit<-mutate(step2_output, year2digit =
                      as.numeric(substr(as.character(ends_with_D),8,9)))
  yr_4digit<-mutate(yr_2digit,
                     year=if_else(year2digit>=70,year2digit+1900,year2digit+2000))
  
  delete_2digit_col<-select(yr_4digit, -year2digit)
  
  col_survey_type<-mutate(delete_2digit_col, survey_type =
                            (substr(as.character(ends_with_D),1,7)))
  
  return(col_survey_type)
}

step3_output <- function_for_step_3(step2_output)

Function for Step 5

We now write a function to do step 5 as follows. This function takes in a data frame and creates a new variable which we name “county_state”. We achieve this using both the mutate() and substr() functions in a similar way as described in the “Data Processing” section.

function_for_step_5<-function(df){
  
  step_5_fn <- mutate(df, county_state = substr(as.character(area_name),nchar(area_name)-1,

  return(step_5_fn)
}

Function for Steps 4, 5 and 6

We now next write a function to output the two tibbles for the non-county data and county data we also add a class to each tibble. This function takes in the output of Step 3 and outputs a list containing the two tibbles for the county data and the non-county data

function_for_step_4_5_6<-function(step3_output){
  non_county_data <- filter(step3_output, !grepl(pattern = ", \\w\\w", area_name))
  
  # we add a class to the non_county tibble called state
 class(non_county_data) <- c("state", class(non_county_data))
  
 county_data <- filter(step3_output, grepl(pattern = ", \\w\\w", area_name)) 
  
  #we add a class to the county tibble called county
 class(county_data) <- c("county", class(county_data))
 
 
 
 county_tibble<-function_for_step_5(county_data)
 
 non_county_tibble<-function_for_step_6(non_county_data)

  return(list(CountyData=county_tibble, NonCountyData=non_county_tibble))
}

function_for_step_4_5_6(step3_output)

Data processing wrapper Function

Finally we create a wrapper function. This function takes in the URL of a .csv file and the optional argument for the variable name.

We also calls the functions for Step 1 to Step 6 written above, and returns the two tibbles.

my_wrapper <- function(url, var_name="enrollment_value"){
  a <- read_csv(url)
  b <- function_for_step_1_2(a)
  c <- function_for_step_3(b)
  d <- function_for_step_4_5_6(c)
  
  return(d)
}

Data combining function to combine the tibbles

The next function takes in the results of the two calls to the data processing wrapper function and combines the tibbles appropriately

my_wrapper_combine<-function(wrapper_call_1,wrapper_call_2){

  
  r<-wrapper_call_1$CountyData
  
  s<-wrapper_call_1$NonCountyData
  
  t<-wrapper_call_2$CountyData
  
  u<-wrapper_call_2$NonCountyData
  
  v<-bind_rows(r,t)
  
  w<-bind_rows(s,u)
  
  return(list(county_combine=v,non_county_combine=w))
}

Writing a Generic Function for Summarizing

Plot function for non-county

We begin dealing with the state plotting method. We write the function below that plots the mean value of the statistic (enrollment for this data set) across the years for each Division. That is, on the x-axis it uses the numeric year value and on the y-axis it uses the mean of the statistic for each Division and numeric year.

Additionally, we remove ERROR from “division” and plot using the ggplot() function.

Firstly we input the data frame, group the data and summarize to subset the data and finally remove ERROR from “division”.

plot.state <- function(df, var_name = "enrollment_value"){
  df%>% 
    
    group_by(get(var_name), division, year)%>%
    summarize(mean1 =  mean(get(var_name)))%>%
    filter(!grepl("ERROR", division)) -> new_df #filter(!grepl("ERROR", division)) removes *ERROR"

  
ggplot(new_df, aes(x = year, y = mean1, color = division)) +
geom_line()

}

Plot for non-county

Here we produce the plot for non-county.

plot.state(county_non_county_combine$non_county_combine)

Plot function for county

For the class county we do a similar plotting function. This function allows the user firstly to specify the state of interest, giving a default value if not specified,

secondly determine whether the “top” or ‘bottom’ most counties should be looked at with a default for ‘top’

thirdly, instruct how many of the “top” or “bottom” will be investigated with a default value of 5

To achieve this we use chaining. First we input the data frame, subset the rows using the filter() function to get the state of interest,

Then we use group_by() and summarize() to group and further subset the data.

We arrange the data using an if/else statement to sort in descending or ascending order based on the specification “top” or “bottom”.

Lastly, we take the the specified amount using the head() function. Since the data is already sorted there is no need for the tail() function. ggplot() creates the plot.

plot.county <- function(df2, state_of_interest = "NC", top_bottom = "top", amount_top_bottom = 5, var_name = "enrollment_value"){
  
  df2 %>% filter(county_state == state_of_interest) %>%
    group_by(get(var_name), area_name, year)%>%
  summarize(mean2 = mean(get(var_name)))%>%
   
  arrange(if (top_bottom == "top"){desc(mean2)} else{mean2})%>%
 
  head(amount_top_bottom)->new_df2
    
  
  ggplot(new_df2, aes(x = year, y = var_name, color = area_name)) +
geom_line()

  
  
}

Plot for county

Here we produce the plot for county.

plot.county(county_non_county_combine$county_combine)
